You don&#39;t need to have absolute positioning. You just need to set display property for the ::before pseudo-element


&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    html,
    body {
      margin: 0;
      height: 100%;
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      flex-direction: column;
    }

    span {
      margin-bottom: 15px;
    }

    .no-absolute::before{
      content: &#39;&#39;;
      display: inline-block;
      width: 10px;
      height: 10px;
      margin-right: 5px;
      border-radius: 50%;
      background-color: #f33;
      cursor: pointer;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;span class=&quot;no-absolute&quot;&gt;No Absolute&lt;/span

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Your `pseudo` element needs a display property. I&#39;ve added `display: block`.



&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    html,
    body {
      margin: 0;
      height: 100%;
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      flex-direction: column;
    }

    span {
      margin-bottom: 15px;
      position: relative;
    }

    .no-absolute::before,
    .absolute::before {
      content: &#39;&#39;;
      width: 10px;
      height: 10px;
      margin-right: 5px;
      border-radius: 50%;
      background-color: #f33;
      cursor: pointer;
      display: block;
    }

    .absolute {
      position: relative;
    }

    .absolute::before {
      position: absolute;
      top: 4px;
      left: -15px;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;span class=&quot;no-absolute&quot;&gt;No Absolute&lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;span class=&quot;absolute&quot;&gt;Absolute&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

The answer is: you need `display` to give the pseudo-element size / shape (either `block` or `inline-block`).  `inline` elements do _not_ accept width / height.

ALTERNATIVELY you could do it with `padding` to give it size / shape, but `display` with `width / height` makes the most sense.



&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    span {
      margin-bottom: 15px;
      position: relative;
    }

    .no-absolute::before,
    .absolute::before {
    display: block;
      content: &#39;&#39;;
      width: 10px;
      height: 10px;
      margin-right: 5px;
      border-radius: 50%;
      background-color: #f33;
      cursor: pointer;
    }


&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;span class=&quot;absolute&quot;&gt;Absolute&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

